# URL-Based Access Control Can Be Circumvented

## Vulnerability Type
Broken Access Control

## Difficulty
Apprentice

## Platform
PortSwigger Web Security Academy

## Goal
Solve the lab by accessing the admin panel and deleting the user "carlos".

## Root Cause
The application relied on front-end restrictions to block access to the `/admin` endpoint. However, the back-end framework trusted the `X-Original-URL` header, allowing attackers to bypass the access control mechanism.

## Exploitation Steps
1. Browse the application
2. Intercept a request using Burp Suite
3. Modify the request header:
4. Add the parameter:X-Original-URL: /admin/deleteUser (because this website allows x-header)
5. Forward the modified request
6. Access the administrative functionality
7. Delete the user "carlos"

## Impact
An attacker can bypass front-end access restrictions and gain unauthorized access to administrative functionality.

## Prevention
- Enforce authorization checks on the back end
- Do not trust rewrite-related headers from users
- Validate all privileged routes server-side
- Restrict internal headers at reverse proxies

## What I Learned
This lab helped me understand how relying only on front-end restrictions can lead to access control bypass vulnerabilities.
